Thought_Process: Because admissions are final at each step (an “immediate acceptance” style process), you should rank first the best nursery where you can actually win the Step 1 seat given others’ first choices and each nursery’s priority order. If you apply to Nursery_B first, you lose in Step 1 to Parent_B (who also applies to B and has higher priority than you there), and then in Step 2 you would be blocked from applying to Nursery_C because it will already be filled in Step 1 by Parent_E (who applies to C first and is accepted). By contrast, if you apply to Nursery_E first, you are top priority at Nursery_E and will be permanently accepted in Step 1, guaranteeing a match. No other strategy can get you Nursery_B or Nursery_C under these rules, so the best achievable outcome is securing Nursery_E immediately.

Because admissions are final immediately and nurseries that fill in Step 1 disappear, the key is to avoid “wasting” an early application on a nursery you are very unlikely to win in the step when it is still available. If I rank Nursery_A first, I lose there to higher-priority applicants (especially Parent_E/Parent_D) while Nursery_C (where I have top priority) will already be taken in Step 1 by another applicant (Parent_E), leaving me to fall to a worse option later. By ranking Nursery_C first, I secure it immediately (I have highest priority at Nursery_C) and it is my best achievable outcome given others’ first choices and priorities. The remaining order follows my true preferences.

Under this immediate-acceptance procedure, you should avoid applying first to a nursery you are unlikely to win because a rejection can leave you applying later only to nurseries that remain unfilled. If you apply to Nursery_B first, you lose to Parent_E or Parent_B (both rank above you in B’s priority), and B will be filled immediately; similarly, Nursery_C is likely filled in step 1 by Parent_E (who prefers C first) or by Parent_B if they apply there. Nursery_E is the best “safe” first choice: no one else ranks E first, so you will be admitted immediately, securing E rather than risking unemployment after rejections at B/C/D. Since admissions are final, placing E first dominates for guaranteeing the best achievable outcome given others’ first choices and priorities.
